Step 2: Exploring / Information Gathering

Use a variety of questions to increase understanding and build rapport.

Exploring

 

Tell me a little bit about your business?

 

•Invites the customer to share information.

•Places few constraints on the type of response were looking for.

•Allows the customer to share what they believe is most important.

Confirming

 

You mentioned customer focus as one of the keys to your success, is that right?

 

•Verifies information youve heard to check understanding.

•Guides the direction of the conversation.

•Gives you the opportunity to ask for clarification.

•Steers the conversation and narrows the scope of the response.

Redirecting

 

I can see how that must have been a difficult time for you and your father. What specifically have you done to manage the transition?

 

•Helps when you have a customer who wanders off track.

•Brings the customer back without you appearing disinterested.

•Uses the words exactly or specifically to help refocus on the topic at hand.

•Flows naturally from what the customer has shared.

Probing / Fact Finding

 

Who else is involved in the purchasing process at your company?

What products do you buy most frequently?

When is your busy season?

Which products are seasonal verses standard purchases?

How do you make the decision to introduce new products to your customers? 

 

•Typically starts with who, what, when, where, which or how.

•Fills in missing information.

•Gives you the clarity you need to provide a recommendation.

Decision / Choice

 

"Have you given any thought to putting together a development plan for your employees?

Do you think Plan A or Plan B would be better for their needs?

 

•Elicits a yes or no response or a specific choice.

•Requires the customer to make a decision.

•Helps to narrow the focus of the conversation and lead the customer to a conclusion.
